oc:kn_2c4a9d9f a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding how many pricing tiers to offer" ;
    oc:directiveContent "2 tiers work for clear SMB vs. Enterprise split; 3 tiers are the industry standard; 4+ tiers add granularity but risk decision paralysis." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Too few tiers leaves money on the table; too many tiers causes choice overload and reduces conversion." .

oc:kn_3e7ae89e a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing between freemium and free trial models" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Avoid freemium when free users provide no network value, marginal serving costs are high, or the product has no viral effects — use free trial instead." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Freemium without network effects creates a large free-user base that consumes resources without converting, devaluing product perception and making future price increases harder." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_452895ba a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding whether to add custom/enterprise pricing" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Enterprise pricing ('Contact Sales') should be added when deal sizes exceed $10k+ ARR, custom contracts are needed, or procurement processes are involved." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Self-serve pricing breaks down at high ARR deals that require legal review, custom SLAs, and implementation support." .

oc:kn_5f72d043 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When packaging tiers for different personas" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Segment customers by company size, use case, sophistication, and industry. 2. Define personas with willingness-to-pay and feature needs. 3. Map features to personas (core features universal, advanced features gated). 4. Set prices that capture value per segment without blocking adoption." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Persona-based packaging ensures each segment finds a tier that matches their needs and budget, maximizing conversion across the customer base." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_7377f4da a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing a 3-tier pricing structure" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the Good-Better-Best framework as the industry standard: Good tier removes barriers to entry, Better tier is the recommended anchor where most customers land, Best tier captures high-value customers at 2-3x the Better price." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Three tiers balance simplicity with revenue capture; anchoring to the middle tier drives most conversions while the premium tier captures high-value segments." .

oc:kn_8c01fb25 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building an enterprise tier" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Enterprise tier must include table-stakes elements (SSO/SAML, audit logs, admin controls, uptime SLA, security certifications) plus value-adds (dedicated support, custom onboarding, training, priority roadmap input) to justify premium pricing." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Enterprise buyers require security and compliance features as baseline; value-adds differentiate from competitors and justify higher pricing." .

oc:kn_ea627969 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SuccessIndicator ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating free trial performance" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Credit card upfront trials yield 40-50% trial-to-paid conversion vs. 15-25% without, but produce lower overall trial volume and better-qualified leads." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The credit card requirement acts as a qualification filter, ensuring trial users have real purchase intent." .

oc:kn_f6359a56 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When defining what differs between tiers" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Differentiate tiers using one or more of: feature gating (advanced features in higher tiers), usage limits (same features, different caps), support level (email → priority → dedicated), or access/customization (API, SSO, branding)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Clear differentiation criteria make the upgrade path obvious and justify higher prices through tangible value differences." .

